                        </div>
                        <div class="post-faq-card">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">What foods should I eat after a hair transplant to improve results?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Focus on high-protein foods (eggs, chicken, lentils), iron-rich sources (spinach, red meat), biotin (nuts, sweet potato), zinc (pumpkin seeds, shellfish), and Omega-3 fatty acids (fatty fish, walnuts). Avoid crash dieting, excessive alcohol, and high-sugar processed foods for at least the first six months post-surgery, as these can suppress hair growth cycles.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="post-faq-card">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">How do I know if my clinic is giving me a realistic density expectation?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">A trustworthy clinic will measure your donor density with a trichoscope, calculate how many grafts your donor area can safely provide, map the recipient area's size, and then give you a specific estimate of achievable density in FU/cm². If a clinic simply promises "full coverage" or "natural thickness" without this analysis, be cautious. Ask for the numbers in writing before you commit.</p>
